1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,260
 So now we're going to build a very simple browser and server in Python.

2
00:00:05,260 --> 00:00:14,400
 Okay, so import a library, import socket, and that just like, you know, import math or import whatever,

3
00:00:14,400 --> 00:00:21,500
 that pulls in a library into Python. Sockets are built into Python, it's very cool, and it's very, very simple.

4
00:00:21,500 --> 00:00:28,700
 So we're, sockets kind of function like files, but they're files that we can send data to and receive data to,

5
00:00:28,700 --> 00:00:32,360
 but when you're using a file in Python, you've got to first open it.

6
00:00:32,360 --> 00:00:37,360
 And so the opening of a file, of a socket, is really a two-step process.

7
00:00:37,360 --> 00:00:44,160
 First you create the socket, and that socket sort of lives in your computer as an endpoint that's not yet finished.

8
00:00:44,160 --> 00:00:48,360
 It's the endpoint that you're going to send and receive data to inside your computer,

9
00:00:48,360 --> 00:00:55,700
 but then we have to actually make the phone call. So socket dot socket, and don't worry too much about this syntax,

10
00:00:55,700 --> 00:01:01,900
 we don't change it. Socket dot socket basically says make a phone, that's what we're making.

11
00:01:01,900 --> 00:01:08,500
 And then mysock.connect, that second line, is dial the phone.

12
00:01:08,500 --> 00:01:16,460
 And we're dialing the phone to a domain name, data.pr4e.org, and a port in that domain name.

13
00:01:16,460 --> 00:01:24,660
 So that is the call. Now, if we made a mistake, right, if we were dialing and not talking to the right server,

14
00:01:24,660 --> 00:01:30,700
 or that server didn't exist, this connect would blow up, meaning we'd make a phone call, a data phone call,

15
00:01:30,700 --> 00:01:34,360
 to a server that doesn't exist. That line is what's going to blow up.

16
00:01:34,360 --> 00:01:40,560
 But as you continue down to the next line, if you continue down to the next line, if it gets that far,

17
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:47,000
 now you put try and accepts around this, but I want to keep this really short, so I'm not putting in all the stuff,

18
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:51,660
 all the error checking. So connect might blow up. Socket dot socket won't blow up,

19
00:01:51,660 --> 00:01:57,900
 because it's like unless you don't have networking at all in your computer, but it's unlikely these days.

20
00:01:57,900 --> 00:02:03,360
 But mysock.connect is like dial the phone, dial the data phone to this endpoint, and it includes the port,

21
00:02:03,360 --> 00:02:08,560
 the port 80 that we talked about before. And now we need to send a command.

22
00:02:08,560 --> 00:02:13,900
 And in this command, it's exactly what we talked about before. It's exactly what we sent via Telnet.

23
00:02:13,900 --> 00:02:21,260
 It's a get followed by a space, followed by our URL, followed by a space, followed by a protocol HTTP/1.0,

24
00:02:21,260 --> 00:02:26,760
 and then we hit the Enter. Now it turns out in network world, you actually hit two things.

25
00:02:26,760 --> 00:02:34,900
 It's the /r/n is a return and a new line. And you have to hit it twice to enter at the beginning of the first line.

26
00:02:34,900 --> 00:02:38,400
 And then remember, we had to put that blank line in because to say no headers.

27
00:02:38,400 --> 00:02:42,960
 Now we would put in between here, we'd put all our headers in there if we were going to do that,

28
00:02:42,960 --> 00:02:46,160
 but we're not going to do that. And then you have to use encode.

29
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:51,600
 Encode means that the data sent across the internet is generally sent in what's called UTF-8.

30
00:02:51,600 --> 00:02:58,660
 Inside of Python, the data is in Unicode so that you can put literally any character in a Python string.

31
00:02:58,660 --> 00:03:05,360
 And then preparing it to send it out across the internet, we encode it into the more dense UTF,

32
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:12,060
 more compressed UTF-8 format rather than we don't send strings across the internet in Unicode in general.

33
00:03:12,060 --> 00:03:18,560
 I mean, it's very rare, but you'd have to control both ends. We want to send them in UTF-8.

34
00:03:18,560 --> 00:03:23,160
 And so the string get blah, blah, blah, that's in the Unicode string in Python.

35
00:03:23,160 --> 00:03:26,560
 And dot encode says convert this into a UTF-8 string.

36
00:03:26,560 --> 00:03:32,760
 And so command cmd is a variable that has a UTF-8 string in it.

37
00:03:32,760 --> 00:03:37,860
 And then we say send. Now remember, I said that you can simultaneously send and receive on these sockets,

38
00:03:37,860 --> 00:03:42,060
 but the protocol tells us whether the first thing we're supposed to do is listen or talk.

39
00:03:42,060 --> 00:03:46,760
 And we're the browser in this case, and so we're supposed to talk first.

40
00:03:46,760 --> 00:03:53,960
 So we send the request out and that's just like you typed it in Telnet because in effect you're scripting Telnet.

41
00:03:53,960 --> 00:03:58,460
 Telnet, we liked Telnet in the old days because it was kind of like a socket.

42
00:03:58,460 --> 00:04:05,660
 I could connect to any host, any port and type things and see if it's broken or not.

43
00:04:05,660 --> 00:04:12,860
 And the protocol says once the server has received the first line, any headers and then the blank line,

44
00:04:12,860 --> 00:04:18,760
 then it's to return it. So then the next part of this is we're going to have a little loop.

45
00:04:18,760 --> 00:04:24,760
 So the protocol tells us we are supposed to receive data until the socket's closed.

46
00:04:24,760 --> 00:04:31,360
 And at the bottom of that Telnet, you saw that it sent a bunch of lines like the four, I think, and then it closed it.

47
00:04:31,360 --> 00:04:35,060
 That's what's going on here. We are retrieving data.

48
00:04:35,060 --> 00:04:40,660
 And then this receive, this actually waits. If the server is coming slower, the network is slow,

49
00:04:40,660 --> 00:04:47,860
 this piece of Python will be, sit, sit, sit, sit, got a little bit, got a little bit up to 512 characters.

50
00:04:47,860 --> 00:04:55,060
 It will wait until it's gotten 512 or it's done and it's got 100 or so.

51
00:04:55,060 --> 00:05:01,160
 But the receive is a blocking, waiting operation in Python, says give me up to the next 512 characters.

52
00:05:01,160 --> 00:05:06,360
 Now, usually the network's so fast that the Python doesn't even wait because the operating system already has it.

53
00:05:06,360 --> 00:05:13,960
 But we get it. And if we get no data whatsoever, that isn't our indication that the network connection,

54
00:05:13,960 --> 00:05:19,460
 the socket has been hung up on, closed by the remote server, and away you go.

55
00:05:19,460 --> 00:05:23,060
 So that's why we are going to break if the length of the data is less than one.

56
00:05:23,060 --> 00:05:28,360
 And if not, we're going to simply print out the data, but we're decoding it.

57
00:05:28,360 --> 00:05:35,760
 And that's because the data that comes in is in UTF-8, but the print statement wants to print Unicode.

58
00:05:35,760 --> 00:05:43,060
 And so decode says, here's a variable that has UTF-8 in it, convert it to Unicode for printing inside of Python.

59
00:05:43,060 --> 00:05:51,060
 So because this data is externalized to us, we encode it before we send it and we decode it when we receive it,

60
00:05:51,060 --> 00:05:57,960
 before we use it, because Python inside itself doesn't use UTF-8, Python inside itself uses Unicode,

61
00:05:57,960 --> 00:06:01,260
 which is awesome and a whole separate conversation.

62
00:06:01,260 --> 00:06:08,260
 I'm just kind of bringing that up to remind you how important it is because we're not going to write much of this in Python, really.

63
00:06:08,260 --> 00:06:12,660
 And all this stuff is taken care of for us in web servers when we get to that point.

64
00:06:12,660 --> 00:06:22,660
 But it's just a good time to review Python's strings and Unicode and encode and decode because it's really important.

65
00:06:22,660 --> 00:06:29,460
 So if you run this and you've got it right, it runs pretty simply.

66
00:06:29,460 --> 00:06:35,760
 Let's get the color back, get it back to yellow here.

67
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:45,760
 So if you run it in your system, Python socket1.py, all the work is done up here before you see your first output.

68
00:06:45,760 --> 00:06:49,560
 And then all this output that you see is just this loop running.

69
00:06:49,560 --> 00:06:53,460
 And what you see is really the exact headers that are coming from this server.

70
00:06:53,460 --> 00:06:59,260
 And then you see a blank line and then you see the actual page that's coming out and you don't see it.

71
00:06:59,260 --> 00:07:03,960
 But at the end here, the connection gets closed and you break out and you're done.

72
00:07:03,960 --> 00:07:10,160
 And then we close our end of the socket. The socket, the far end was already closed.

73
00:07:10,160 --> 00:07:13,160
 That's how we know to stop reading data.

74
00:07:13,160 --> 00:07:20,760
 And then we hang ourselves up so that our local system does not end up with a bunch of half hung up phone calls.

75
00:07:20,760 --> 00:07:26,560
 And so that's basically how we talk to a socket in Python.

76
00:07:26,560 --> 00:07:33,560
 Now, that was literally 10 years ago how I would debug applications.

77
00:07:33,560 --> 00:07:37,560
 I would like Telnet or write a little thing like that and dump all the headers.

78
00:07:37,560 --> 00:07:40,260
 And that got really tiring, really boring, really tiring.

79
00:07:40,260 --> 00:07:44,060
 And so browser developer mode is going to be your friend.

80
00:07:44,060 --> 00:07:47,360
 In a way, browser developer mode, and I'm going to have a separate video on this.

81
00:07:47,360 --> 00:07:54,560
 Browser developer mode lets you look at the sent headers, the received headers, the received data, the sent data, what URL it went to.

82
00:07:54,560 --> 00:08:01,060
 And it's super awesome, especially because a lot of web pages have like 40 to 150 request response cycles.

83
00:08:01,060 --> 00:08:03,560
 So you don't want to debug them all by hand.

84
00:08:03,560 --> 00:08:08,460
 You just let the browser do its thing and say, what was that second one and what went wrong in the second one?

85
00:08:08,460 --> 00:08:13,660
 I spent a lot of time when I'm debugging web applications using the developer mode.

86
00:08:13,660 --> 00:08:17,060
 And that's why I have a special little video that gets you familiar with it.

